observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE direct/cause the:
MT to:
Obtain the addresses of payees for notification of the return of stale checks in their possession for replacement;
Prospectively, closely monitor and send written notices to the payees one month before the checks become stale;
Ensure that stale checks are reported and attached to the RCI prepared on the period of cancellation;
Return the original disbursement vouchers (DV) and supporting documents of unclaimed stale checks to the MA;
Issue a replacement check upon submission/presentation of the stale check in the hands of payees; and
Coordinate or report to the bank about the 8 checks in her name and encashed by the bank but which were not drawn against the depository account of the LGU as per bank statements and coordinate with the MA about the result of the foregoing.
MA to
Prepare the JEV to revert back the transaction to the appropriate cash and liability accounts upon the return the original DVs and supporting documents of unclaimed stale checks in the Municipal Treaurer’s Office (MTO); and
Take appropriate actions, if necessary, on the results under Recommendation No. 1(f) above to be coordinated by the MT.

We recommended that the LCE require the MT to:
Strictly enforce the preparation of individual RAAF specifying the quantity of the accountable forms received, issued or cancelled as of the end of month by each RCO;
Consolidate the RAAFs and submit the same together with the individual RAAFs to the AT not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month in order to facilitate monthly verification of accountable forms;
Stop the practice of sharing booklets of AFs. The transfer of AFs from one RCO to another shall be supported with the proper recording of the transfer of accountability so that accountability to AFs are fixed; and
Produce the triplicate copies of the 177 unaccounted AFs and present same to the AT.
We also recommended strict compliance with Section 86 of LTOM.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require an explanation from the heads of offices on the absence in the APP or the Supplemental APP of the specific appropriation for the purchase of airline tickets;
Direct all department heads/end users to include in their Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) all acquisitions of airline tickets planned for the year and submit the same to the BAC Secretariat for consolidation and basis for preparation of the APP;
Ensure that no procurement shall be authorized and undertaken unless it is in accordance with an approved APP or supplemental APP; and
Instruct all officials and employees to purchase airline tickets directly from commercial airlines and service providers as provided under Section V, Item b of Annex H of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

2.9 	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries for the reclassification of the completed projects from CIP account to the appropriate PPE accounts and to recognize the corresponding depreciation for the completed projects;
Municipal Accountant to transfer the cost of the completed projects under the Trust Fund to the General Fund;
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer to reconcile their records regularly to determine the status and correct balances of the CIP and PPE accounts; and
Municipal Accountant to draw appropriate journal entries to recognize the Construction Materials Inventory upon purchase of construction materials.

4.16 	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require:
The Municipal Accountant to cause the preparation of adjusting entries of reconciling items with available documentation or reference;
The Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the BRS for all bank accounts of the Municipality within the reglementary period;
The Municipal Treasurer to maintain cashbooks on all accounts and conduct reconciliation with accounting records to reflect reliable/actual balance of cash presented in the financial statements; and
Municipal Treasurer to retrieve DVs and supporting documents of the identified stale checks and present the same to the Municipal Accountant for the preparation of appropriate adjusting entries in the books of accounts.

13.25 	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:
Responsible officials and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that claims for meals and snacks are supported with sufficient and relevant documents to substantiate actual deliveries and that the activities pertaining to the claims are official;
LGU officials and employees to exercise austerity, economy and restraint in the procurement of meals during government activities;
Requesting officers to ensure that program designs are properly supported with prospective attendees to arrive at the most proximate number of participants, and for the said number to be accordingly stated in the Purchase Requests;
Requesting officers and the BAC Chairperson to include a clause in the contracts that payments for meals will be based on the actual number of event attendees/meal recipients; and
Concerned officials and employees to be meticulous and judicious in the preparation of their Annual Procurement Plan and ensure that all necessary information required are reflected therein for its continuous relevance and usefulness as a planning and control tool

We recommended that the LCE require the MT to:
a. Strictly enforce the preparation of individual RAAF specifying the quantity of the accountable forms received, issued or cancelled as of the end of month by each RCO;
b. Consolidate the RAAFs and submit the same together with the individual RAAFs to the Audit Team not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month in order to facilitate monthly verification of accountable forms;
c. Stop the practice of sharing booklets of AFs. The transfer of AFs from one RCO to another shall be supported with the proper recording of the transfer of accountability so that accountability to AFs are fixed; and
d. Locate and produce the 177 unaccounted accountable forms.
We also recommend strict compliance with Section 86 of LTOM.

We recommend the LCE:
a. Require an explanation from the heads of offices on the absence in the APP of the specific appropriation for the purchase of airline tickets;
b. Direct all department heads/end users to include in their Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) all acquisitions of airline tickets planned for the year and submit the same to the BAC Secretariat for consolidation and basis for preparation of the APP;
c. Ensure that no procurement shall be authorized and undertaken unless it is in accordance with an approved APP or supplemental APP; and
d. Instruct all officials and employees to purchase airline tickets directly from commercial airlines and service providers as provided under Section V, Item b of Annex H of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended that the LCE direct/cause the MT to:
a. Obtain the addresses of payees for notification of the return of stale checks in their possession for replacement;
b. Prospectively, closely monitor and send written notices to the payees one month before the checks become stale;
c. Ensure that stale checks are reported and attached to the RCI prepared on the period of cancellation;
d. Return the original DVs and supporting documents of unclaimed stale checks to the Municipal Accountant;
e. Issue a replacement check upon submission/presentation of the stale check in the hands of payees; and
f. Coordinate or report to the bank about 8 checks in her name and encashed by the bank but which were not drawn against the depository account of the LGU as per bank statements and coordinate with the Municipal Accountant about the result of the foregoing.
We also recommended that the MA prepare the JEV to revert back the transaction to the appropriate cash and liability accounts upon the return of the original DVs and supporting documents of unclaimed stale checks in the MTO; and take appropriate actions, if necessary, on the results under Recommendation no. 1(f) above to be coordinated by the MT.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a.) Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical inventory of all the PPE and prepare and submit the required report thereon, in the proper form, summarized according to type of PPE and properly accomplished in all particulars, in accordance with Section 124 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I and Item VI of COA Circular No. 2015-008. Any discrepancies between the inventory report and the accounting and property records should be investigated and make the necessary adjustments where the error was committed;
b.) Inventory Committee and the OIC-Municipal Accountant to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records of Local Road Networks in order to immediately determine the cause/s and details of the difference amounting to P(22,760,720.61), thereafter, make necessary adjustments where the error was committed;
c.) OIC-GSO and the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and updated PCs and PPELCs, respectively, and issue ARE to the requesting office;
d.) OIC-Municipal Accountant to conduct a detailed review of the CIP-Infrastructure Asset account in the Trust Fund books so that the dormant balance of P9,230,949.88 can be adjusted accordingly to its correct account;
e.) OIC-GSO to maintain Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep updating the LRNPC for all roads and its components; and
f.) OIC-Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system of the Municipality at year-end.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

all concerned officials and employees to liquidate their outstanding CAs as of December 31, 2020;

the Municipal Accountant (MA) to send demand letters to those employees who are active in service with unliquidated cash advances totaling ₱57,576;

request formally for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs aging 10 years and more totaling ₱39,959 and submit the same to COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor.  In this connection, we recommended that the LCE direct the MA to prepare an aging of unliquidated CAs to support the request for write-off, indicating in the remarks column the existence of the applicable conditions as in indicated on Section 7.4 of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

all concerned officials and employees strict compliance with Sections 4.1.2, 4.1.3 and 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 197-002.

We recommended that the LCE:

instruct the MA to remit immediately to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth the total amount of ₱0.52 million;

instruct the MT to facilitate regular transmittal of DV’s to the MAO for timely recording of transactions;

direct the MA to constantly follow-up/coordinate with the concerned GOCCs the regular data updating of employees’ records for correct billing statements; and

require the MA and MT to comply strictly with Section 6(b) and Section 3.6 Rule II, of RA 8291, Section 3(a), Rule VII of RA 9679 and Section 20 (b), Rule III, IRR of National Health Insurance Act of 1995.

